It's really a fantastic process.

00:30:45.160 --> 00:30:46.750
Very good.

00:30:46.750 --> 00:30:49.330
Let's go back to
the board and talk

00:30:49.330 --> 00:30:52.900
about this more theoretically.

00:30:52.900 --> 00:30:55.140
We have sort of answered
a question here.

00:30:55.140 --> 00:30:57.720
How does a cell type
express it's code?

00:30:57.720 --> 00:31:00.690
Well, not all at once,
over time and over a series

00:31:00.690 --> 00:31:03.290
of many steps.

00:31:03.290 --> 00:31:05.530
But that's not actually
the whole on answer.

00:31:08.190 --> 00:31:11.240
And so let's rephrase
the question to make

00:31:11.240 --> 00:31:12.440
it a little more precise.

00:31:12.440 --> 00:31:16.850
And I've rephrased it by asking,
what tells a specific cell type

00:31:16.850 --> 00:31:18.005
to express its code?

00:31:24.720 --> 00:31:29.430
What tells a specific cell
type to express its code?

00:31:40.590 --> 00:31:42.521
And the answer is--

00:31:42.521 --> 00:31:44.520
it's just not going to
be really helpful to you,

00:31:44.520 --> 00:31:45.520
but it will in a moment.

00:31:45.520 --> 00:31:48.180
The answer is that there
are a bunch of inputs.

00:31:48.180 --> 00:31:50.610
There are a bunch
of instructions

00:31:50.610 --> 00:31:51.670
that the cell gets.

00:31:58.060 --> 00:32:00.510
And let's write this out in
a kind of theoretical way.

00:32:00.510 --> 00:32:02.970
We'll get to the
molecules in a moment.

00:32:02.970 --> 00:32:04.860
Here again are our
uncommitted cells.

00:32:09.900 --> 00:32:13.350
And they can be exposed to a
number of different molecules.

00:32:13.350 --> 00:32:15.990
The inputs-- let me
just come clean here.

00:32:15.990 --> 00:32:18.480
The inputs are
specific molecules.

00:32:18.480 --> 00:32:20.730
And as you'll see in
a moment, they all

00:32:20.730 --> 00:32:24.660
have got something to do with
cell signaling or regulating

00:32:24.660 --> 00:32:27.390
gene expression.

00:32:27.390 --> 00:32:29.510
These uncommitted
cells can be exposed

00:32:29.510 --> 00:32:30.850
to many different inputs.

00:32:30.850 --> 00:32:35.060
Let's take three
different inputs.

00:32:35.060 --> 00:32:40.760
We'll call them
input 1, 2, and 3.

00:32:40.760 --> 00:32:45.770
And these inputs through
many steps and changes

00:32:45.770 --> 00:32:48.790
in gene expression.

00:32:48.790 --> 00:32:51.660
And the inputs can be composite.

00:32:51.660 --> 00:32:54.570
They don't have to
be a single thing.

00:32:54.570 --> 00:33:02.610
We'll take those cells into
differentiated cell type 1,

00:33:02.610 --> 00:33:07.520
cell type 2, or cell type 3.

00:33:12.500 --> 00:33:14.930
And cell type 1--

00:33:14.930 --> 00:33:17.700
you know, to belabor
this, we'll express

00:33:17.700 --> 00:33:24.440
code 1, cell type
2 code 2 et cetera.

00:33:24.440 --> 00:33:27.560
As these decisions are
made similar to the kinds

00:33:27.560 --> 00:33:31.190
of decisions we've looked at
in biochemistry previously.

00:33:31.190 --> 00:33:33.200
There can be interactions.

00:33:33.200 --> 00:33:38.420
And so it may be that as cell
type 1 develops, it's actually

00:33:38.420 --> 00:33:45.734
inhibits the formation
of cell type 2.

00:33:45.734 --> 00:33:49.040
And cell type 2,
in turn, might be

00:33:49.040 --> 00:33:53.640
an inhibitor of the
formation of cell type 3.

00:33:53.640 --> 00:33:56.660
So there are interactions
between cells.

00:33:56.660 --> 00:34:00.500
So the inputs can be composite.

00:34:00.500 --> 00:34:12.650
They can composed of several
molecules factors if you like.

00:34:16.489 --> 00:34:22.310
And there's crosstalk,
just like the crosstalk

00:34:22.310 --> 00:34:24.830
between the receptors
that we talked about

00:34:24.830 --> 00:34:26.690
in cell-cell signaling.

00:34:26.690 --> 00:34:31.429
And that's not surprising,
because in fact the inputs

00:34:31.429 --> 00:34:33.650
includes cell-cell
signaling molecules.

00:34:33.650 --> 00:34:38.730
So there's ligands and receptors
that we spoke about previously.

00:34:38.730 --> 00:34:39.769
So what are the inputs?

00:34:49.139 --> 00:34:51.060
And there are two.

00:34:51.060 --> 00:34:57.000
One are signals that
act between cells, just

00:34:57.000 --> 00:34:58.950
like we've been
talking about in cell

00:34:58.950 --> 00:35:00.870
biology, cell-cell signaling.

00:35:04.550 --> 00:35:08.080
And wherever you talk
about cell-cell signaling,

00:35:08.080 --> 00:35:10.870
it is implicit that you're
talking about interactions

00:35:10.870 --> 00:35:13.290
between cells.

00:35:13.290 --> 00:35:24.450
Ligands, which in development
are sometimes called inducers,

00:35:24.450 --> 00:35:25.700
acts on the receptor.

00:35:31.100 --> 00:35:36.260
And the outcome is
to change cell fate.

00:35:40.330 --> 00:35:42.880
This is a subset of the
signaling interactions

00:35:42.880 --> 00:35:45.430
we talked about previously,
where the response

00:35:45.430 --> 00:35:48.760
here or the response
previously was manyfold,

00:35:48.760 --> 00:35:51.940
the response here would
be to change cell fate.

00:35:51.940 --> 00:35:54.790
But there's a second
kind of input.

00:35:54.790 --> 00:36:05.710
And those are the molecules
that are cell autonomous,

00:36:05.710 --> 00:36:11.620
also referred to as
being inherited factors

00:36:11.620 --> 00:36:15.970
and referred to in
development as determinants.

00:36:15.970 --> 00:36:26.030
And these determinants-- this
is what cell autonomous means--

00:36:26.030 --> 00:36:27.485
act within cells.

00:36:34.670 --> 00:36:37.880
And so they're not going to
be ligands some receptors.

00:36:37.880 --> 00:36:40.470
They will be
things, for example,

00:36:40.470 --> 00:36:41.930
like transcription factors.

00:36:49.710 --> 00:36:57.320
Furthermore, both
determinants and inducers

00:36:57.320 --> 00:37:00.470
can act in a concentration
dependent way

00:37:00.470 --> 00:37:04.610
so that a small amount
would give you one cell fate

00:37:04.610 --> 00:37:08.120
and a larger amount would give
you a different cell fate.

00:37:13.590 --> 00:37:16.110
So it can be
concentration dependent.

00:37:21.730 --> 00:37:25.110
And in the cases where a
signal or a determinant

00:37:25.110 --> 00:37:29.110
is concentration dependent,
it gets a special name.

00:37:29.110 --> 00:37:34.030
It's referred to as a
morphogen, for historical, not

00:37:34.030 --> 00:37:35.960
particularly logical reasons.

00:37:35.960 --> 00:37:38.790
But if you see the
term you'll know.

00:37:38.790 --> 00:37:42.120
And finally, before
we go to some slides,

00:37:42.120 --> 00:37:45.720
one can find groups of
these inputs, groups

00:37:45.720 --> 00:37:48.750
of these regulatory molecules.

00:37:48.750 --> 00:37:57.030
So all of these inputs, all
of these other regulatory

00:37:57.030 --> 00:38:00.630
molecules or regulatory factors.

00:38:04.370 --> 00:38:07.040
And they can act
spatially in groups.

00:38:07.040 --> 00:38:10.460
So you can find regions of
the developing embryo, where

00:38:10.460 --> 00:38:13.800
there are groups of these
molecules acting together.

00:38:13.800 --> 00:38:16.520
And where you find these
groups, that particular region

00:38:16.520 --> 00:38:20.630
of the embryo may have a
powerful effect in influencing

00:38:20.630 --> 00:38:22.940
the cells which form around it.

00:38:22.940 --> 00:38:26.720
And that region, that group
of factors in one region

00:38:26.720 --> 00:38:28.520
that can influence
its surroundings

00:38:28.520 --> 00:38:31.150
is called an organizer.

00:38:31.150 --> 00:38:40.660
So groups of signals,
which are localized,

00:38:40.660 --> 00:38:54.590
that is in one place,
in one group of cells

00:38:54.590 --> 00:39:05.790
can influence the
surrounding cells

00:39:05.790 --> 00:39:07.600
and is termed an organizer.

00:39:10.780 --> 00:39:15.550
And there are many organizers
in the body both in the embryo

00:39:15.550 --> 00:39:17.170
and in ourselves
as we'll discuss

00:39:17.170 --> 00:39:19.890
when we talk about stem cells.

00:39:19.890 --> 00:39:22.510
Examples of organizers,
I'll show you in a moment.

00:39:22.510 --> 00:39:24.630
There's something called
the Spemann organizer,

00:39:24.630 --> 00:39:25.740
which is very famous.

00:39:25.740 --> 00:39:29.070
And some of you may have
learned about that previously.

00:39:29.070 --> 00:39:32.910
And then there are
regions, for example,

00:39:32.910 --> 00:39:37.350
in the forebrain, the
developing cerebrum,

00:39:37.350 --> 00:39:39.810
where there is an organizer
that actually tells

00:39:39.810 --> 00:39:42.960
the different parts of you
developing higher cortical

00:39:42.960 --> 00:39:44.940
function to form.

00:39:44.940 --> 00:39:48.690
So let's look at some slides
and some of your handouts.

00:39:51.590 --> 00:39:53.210
And I drew these
for you, because I

00:39:53.210 --> 00:39:56.030
thought it was really
important that you got them.

00:39:56.030 --> 00:40:00.500
Here is localized determinants,
localized regulators

00:40:00.500 --> 00:40:01.440
called determinants.

00:40:01.440 --> 00:40:03.690
And you see the idea here.

00:40:03.690 --> 00:40:04.530
This is important.

00:40:04.530 --> 00:40:06.360
This isn't on the board.

00:40:06.360 --> 00:40:11.150
Here's the mother
cell with these boxes,

00:40:11.150 --> 00:40:15.000
where these boxes represent
some kind of regulatory factor.

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:18.290
And you can see I've drawn
them on one side of the cell,

00:40:18.290 --> 00:40:21.740
such that when that cell
divides one of the daughters

00:40:21.740 --> 00:40:24.860
doesn't get them and
one of them does.

00:40:24.860 --> 00:40:28.730
And if the boxes are
regulatory factors,

00:40:28.730 --> 00:40:32.180
the daughter's cell that gets
them will go on to do something

00:40:32.180 --> 00:40:34.170
different than the
one that doesn't.

00:40:34.170 --> 00:40:37.860
And you can get two different
cell types coming out of this.

00:40:37.860 --> 00:40:41.460
And I've listed examples
of the many different kinds

00:40:41.460 --> 00:40:46.060
of factors that can
be determinants.

00:40:46.060 --> 00:40:48.780
Here's a real example.

00:40:48.780 --> 00:40:51.840
This is an early worm embryo.

00:40:51.840 --> 00:40:53.880
Remember, I told you
about Professor Horvitz,

00:40:53.880 --> 00:40:57.060
who got the Nobel Prize
for discovering cell death

00:40:57.060 --> 00:40:58.410
processes.

00:40:58.410 --> 00:41:01.320
This is the same
animal he works on.

00:41:01.320 --> 00:41:06.950
And on the top panels are
nuclei stained in blue

00:41:06.950 --> 00:41:08.870
with this dye called dappy.

00:41:08.870 --> 00:41:09.980
Here's the zygote.

00:41:09.980 --> 00:41:12.630
Here's the two cell embryo
and the 32 cell embryo.

00:41:12.630 --> 00:41:16.610
And you can see that there's
a nucleus in every cell.

00:41:16.610 --> 00:41:18.950
On the bottom are
some determinants

00:41:18.950 --> 00:41:20.950
that are called pea granules.

00:41:20.950 --> 00:41:24.350
Pea granules are composites
of protein and RNA.

00:41:24.350 --> 00:41:27.860
And they are regulators of
where the future germ cells will

00:41:27.860 --> 00:41:30.140
form, the future egg and sperm.

00:41:30.140 --> 00:41:32.690
Look how these germ-- look
how these pea granules

00:41:32.690 --> 00:41:34.820
segregate during development.

00:41:34.820 --> 00:41:39.140
Here they are on one side of
the embryo, even in the zygote,

00:41:39.140 --> 00:41:40.820
and then the zygote splits.

00:41:40.820 --> 00:41:42.850
Look, one of the two
cells gets them more

00:41:42.850 --> 00:41:44.300
and the other does nothing.

00:41:44.300 --> 00:41:48.560
And at the 32 cell stage, there
is one cell out of 32 that

00:41:48.560 --> 00:41:50.420
has all of the pea granules.

00:41:50.420 --> 00:41:52.580
And they've been
excluded or degraded

00:41:52.580 --> 00:41:55.310
from the rest of the embryo.

00:41:55.310 --> 00:41:57.260
And that is a really
beautiful example,

00:41:57.260 --> 00:41:59.360
perhaps the most
beautiful example

00:41:59.360 --> 00:42:02.600
of determinants segregating.

00:42:02.600 --> 00:42:05.710
Here's another one,
the signaling factor

00:42:05.710 --> 00:42:08.360
secreted by neighboring cells.

00:42:08.360 --> 00:42:12.110
Uncommitted to cells over
time will do something.

00:42:12.110 --> 00:42:15.650
There's enough transcription
factors and regulatory factors

00:42:15.650 --> 00:42:17.570
in all cells that
over time they'll

00:42:17.570 --> 00:42:20.180
go on to differentiate
into something if they're

00:42:20.180 --> 00:42:21.830
normal cells.

00:42:21.830 --> 00:42:25.760
But there's a signaling cell
telling an uncommitted cell

00:42:25.760 --> 00:42:31.790
to activate a signaling pathway
and go on and make cell type 2.

00:42:31.790 --> 00:42:33.650
And these are the
inducers, which

00:42:33.650 --> 00:42:38.750
are ligands binding to
receptors and changing sulfate.

00:42:38.750 --> 00:42:42.260
These signaling pathways can
act in a concentration dependent

00:42:42.260 --> 00:42:46.630
way, as seen on that screen.

00:42:46.630 --> 00:42:49.610
And here is the notion
of a morphogen, where

00:42:49.610 --> 00:42:52.230
a high ligand
concentration will give

00:42:52.230 --> 00:42:56.250
an output of cell type 2
and low ligand concentration

00:42:56.250 --> 00:42:57.810
and output of cell type 3.

00:42:57.810 --> 00:43:01.320
And we touched on how this works
molecularly, previously, it's

00:43:01.320 --> 00:43:03.420
not well understood
and is complicated.

00:43:06.070 --> 00:43:10.440
This is the most
famous example of cells

00:43:10.440 --> 00:43:14.040
that can go on and tell
other cells what to become.

00:43:14.040 --> 00:43:17.520
It's a group of cells that was
termed the organizer before it

00:43:17.520 --> 00:43:20.640
was clear that there were
actually lots of organizers.

00:43:20.640 --> 00:43:24.130
And they organized was defined
by a graduate student Hilde

00:43:24.130 --> 00:43:28.620
Mangold, together with
her advisor, Hans Spemann.

00:43:28.620 --> 00:43:32.250
Mangold, unfortunately, went on
and was killed in an explosion.

00:43:32.250 --> 00:43:34.440
Spemann went on to
get the first Nobel

00:43:34.440 --> 00:43:37.800
Prize for developmental
biology in 1935.

00:43:37.800 --> 00:43:39.180
It's never seemed fair.

00:43:39.180 --> 00:43:41.010
It isn't fair, anyway.

00:43:41.010 --> 00:43:43.500
That is a sad story.

00:43:43.500 --> 00:43:47.430
Spemann was the preeminent
developmental biologist

00:43:47.430 --> 00:43:48.690
in the 1920s.

00:43:48.690 --> 00:43:52.530
And this is the finding
that Dr. Mangold made.

00:43:52.530 --> 00:43:58.440
She took an embryo and she
removed from the embryo--

00:43:58.440 --> 00:44:00.260
so you not only do
you see my calendar--

00:44:00.260 --> 00:44:03.980
you get an insight into
the rest of my life.

00:44:03.980 --> 00:44:08.210
My husband is a professor
over at that other university.

00:44:08.210 --> 00:44:13.760
So we have competing
teaching schedules today.

00:44:13.760 --> 00:44:18.920
So Dr. Mangold took a group
of cells from the future back

00:44:18.920 --> 00:44:21.380
of the embryo-- we'll talk
about this next time--

00:44:21.380 --> 00:44:24.470
and she transplanted
them into another embryo.

00:44:24.470 --> 00:44:26.420
She transplanted
them into the belly.

00:44:26.420 --> 00:44:28.700
So she took back
cells and put them

00:44:28.700 --> 00:44:31.380
in the future belly
of a host embryo.

00:44:31.380 --> 00:44:33.080
So there's a donor and a host.

00:44:33.080 --> 00:44:35.540
And she could see the difference
between these embryos,

00:44:35.540 --> 00:44:37.430
because they had
different pigmentation.

00:44:37.430 --> 00:44:38.555
They were different colors.

00:44:41.040 --> 00:44:43.310
And then she let them
go on and develop.

00:44:43.310 --> 00:44:45.560
And this was a hugely
difficult experiment

00:44:45.560 --> 00:44:48.060
in those days for
technical reasons.

00:44:48.060 --> 00:44:50.660
But over a period of
a couple of months,

00:44:50.660 --> 00:44:52.280
these embryos developed.

00:44:52.280 --> 00:44:55.350
And what she found was
this peculiar embryo,

00:44:55.350 --> 00:44:57.740
which is a conjoined twin.

00:44:57.740 --> 00:44:59.810
And she could show
by looking to see

00:44:59.810 --> 00:45:01.910
where the cells she
had transplanted in

00:45:01.910 --> 00:45:05.570
were, that there was this host
embryo that was made of all

00:45:05.570 --> 00:45:07.790
the original host tissue.

00:45:07.790 --> 00:45:10.220
And there was another
embryo joined to it

00:45:10.220 --> 00:45:13.970
in this orientation, but
that only a little bit

00:45:13.970 --> 00:45:19.130
of the second embryo actually
came from the donor cells.

00:45:19.130 --> 00:45:22.940
Most of the second embryo
came from the host cells.

00:45:22.940 --> 00:45:26.980
And this was epiphanal,
because she could understand

00:45:26.980 --> 00:45:29.800
that those donor cells
had told the host

00:45:29.800 --> 00:45:32.540
tissue to make another embryo.

00:45:32.540 --> 00:45:35.530
It was an extraordinary
unprecedented finding,

00:45:35.530 --> 00:45:39.780
and it gave the notion
that cells can tell

00:45:39.780 --> 00:45:42.030
other cells what to become.

00:45:42.030 --> 00:45:45.180
Does this happen in
other animals for sure?

00:45:45.180 --> 00:45:48.210
This is from a colleague
of mine Jerry Thompson, who

00:45:48.210 --> 00:45:51.830
made these conjoined twin
frog embryos by organizer

00:45:51.830 --> 00:45:53.420
transplants.

00:45:53.420 --> 00:45:55.020
Does that happen in humans?

00:45:55.020 --> 00:45:55.590
It does.

00:45:55.590 --> 00:46:00.240
Conjoined twins come from,
we believe, organizers

00:46:00.240 --> 00:46:02.460
that have split
and have given rise

00:46:02.460 --> 00:46:05.220
to two embryos, which
don't separate properly

00:46:05.220 --> 00:46:05.930
from one another.

00:46:08.540 --> 00:46:13.840
And we will stop there
and continue on Monday.

